{{Infobox software | name = WIRIS | logo = | screenshot = | caption = | collapsible = | author = | developer = Maths for More | released = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | discontinued = | latest release version = | latest release date = <!--{{Start date and age|2006|02|13|df=yes}}--> | programming language = | operating system = | platform = | size = | language = | status = | genre = [[Mathematical software]] | license = | website = {{URL|http://www.wiris.com/en/|link}} }} '''WIRIS''' is a set of proprietary HTML-based [[JavaScript]] [[programming tool|tools]] which can author and edit [[mathematical formula]]s,<ref name="XhafaCaballé2010">{{cite book|author1=Fatos Xhafa|author2=Santi Caballé|author3=Ajith Abraham |author4=Thanasis Daradoumis |author5=Angel Alejandro Juan Perez |title=Computational Intelligence for Technology Enhanced Learning|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RohK1XQNe1IC|date=18 February 2010|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-11223-2}}</ref> execute [[mathematical problem]]s<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/0020739X.2011.583396 | volume=42 | title=Random learning units using WIRIS quizzes in Moodle | year=2011 | journal=International Journal of Mathematical Education in Science and Technology | pages=751–763 | author=Mora Ángel, Mérida Enrique, Eixarch Ramon}}</ref> and show [[Graph of a function|mathematical graphics]] on the [[Cartesian coordinate system]]. WIRIS equation editor<ref name="CaretteDixon2009">{{cite book|author1=Jacques Carette|author2=Lucas Dixon|author3=Claudio Sacerdoti Coen |author4=Stephen Watt |title=Intelligent Computer Mathematics: 16th Symposium, Calculemus 2009, 8th International Conference, MKM 2009, Grand Bend, Canada, July 6-12, 2009, Proceedings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IKNmax4dZ70C|date=6 July 2009|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-02614-0}}</ref> is a native [[browser application]], with a light server-side, that supports both [[MathML]] and [[LaTeX]].
